{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b9c16c5-e993-4e7b-a5a6-7685a0299f03","content":"Use **`dotnet run`**, not `dotnet test`.\n\nThe `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` package works with the Microsoft Testing Platform's direct execution mode. Since your project has `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` enabled, running:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj\n```\n\nstarts a persistent process that watches for file changes and re-runs affected tests automatically. `dotnet test` runs tests and exits, so it won't benefit from hot reload.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cf017b7a-131a-4891-9630-3d0540bed257","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` package installed. This is the Microsoft Testing Platform hot reload extension. \n\nWith `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` set to `true`, the project uses the newer Microsoft Testing Platform. The hot reload feature for tests works with `dotnet run` (not `dotnet test`), because hot reload requires the Microsoft Testing Platform's direct execution mode.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. With the Microsoft Testing Platform:\n\n- `dotnet test` uses the VSTest compatibility layer\n- `dotnet run` runs the test project directly as an executable using the Microsoft Testing Platform\n\n\n- The hot reload extension specifically needs `dotnet run` because it requires a persistent process that can watch for file changes and automatically re-run tests when they're modified.\n\nSo the answer is to use `dotnet run` to take advantage of hot reload functionality.","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"A810:1AA4EA:62C32FA:6B414F7:6A034B82"},"id":"e5ce570f-24d4-44e6-a0e0-003fd5df365b","timestamp":"2026-05-12T15:47:28.991Z","parentId":"59d765ed-f048-47d1-9a65-8c337f20685f"}
